❄️PATTERN RELEASE!❄️ Introducing the “Snow Place Like Home” quilt block! There are so many reasons why I love this pattern. Here are just a few:

❄️ It’s a companion piece to my “Home for the Holidays” pattern, though you don’t have to own both to enjoy it. If you already own my “Home for the Holidays” pattern, this will provide you an additional house design —an A-Frame! You can also swap out any of the other designs since they all finish with the same general dimensions.
❄️ This pattern is customizable! It includes several window and door options to make your A-frame your very own! You can use the house block on its own, or you can include the snow globe portion, too.
❄️ It’s a large pattern. Finishing at approx. 16” x 14 1/4”, it would only take a few blocks to create a quilt. Add a border, and it’s perfect for a pillow.
❄️ It’s not just for Christmas. Fill the snow globe background with a fun bat print, and it’s a Halloween pattern! Or hearts for Valentine’s Day! It’s all up to you!

My patterns are meant to inspire and promote your creativity. I like to provide options for you to make my designs your own. I really hope you enjoy this one!

Several of you provided the name suggestion, but one of you mentioned it first. A big thanks to @stitcharmony! I’ll be in touch with your FREE copy of the pattern. 💕

“Snow Place Like Home” is available NOW! Grab your copy today in my Etsy shop. Link in bio.

I was a pretty tough kid. I grew up in rural Indiana, twenty minutes from anything you’d call a town. Neighbors were spread out between corn and bean fields, and the majority of the (few) kids that lived along our road were boys. I grew up playing sports, catching crayfish and minnows in the river behind our house, digging for worms and nightcrawlers, fishing along the riverbanks, playing hide and seek in the woods at dusk. I wasn’t afraid of much in the outdoors, but moths were one exception.

How can one catch and bait fish hooks with worms and grasshoppers, yet swat erratically and squeal around moths? Good question. 😆 The fix? Give them a cute name and personality to boot! Thus, “Mrs. Miller” was born.

My parents (oddly) decided to start calling moths “Mrs. Miller.” Why? I’ve no idea. But it worked! For some reason, calling those little bugs by name and imagining them as harmless little (elderly, in my imagination) ladies, made everything okay. So for most of my life, moths have been called Mrs. Miller or simply Millers (if more than one is present). My husband even calls them by name. 🤣

So this is my “Mrs. Miller” project. An ode to the beauty of nature and imagination. 💕

Pattern: “Moth Eclipse” by @woollypetals.

I was going to write a feel-good caption here, but I just finished reading an article about how women in this country —this time, young girls— are yet again under attack. You know, I’m raising a young woman in this household, and so matters that have always meant a great deal to me as a woman, are now of even greater priority and importance. The fact that our rights and freedoms are even on the table for discussion at all in this day and age enrages me, as I know it angers many of you.

When I started this project, I wondered why I was making a pink quilt. While I love the color, none of us in this house would typically use a pink quilt as decor. Today, I couldn’t love it more. The world could use more pink quilts. And common sense. And compassion.

“Strong women.
May we know them,
may we be them,
may we raise them.”

💖

I was recently asked how my Tall Tales acrylic template works, so I thought I’d explain here for anyone who’s unsure. It’s actually very easy. Simply place the template over the section of fabric you’d like to fussy cut. (Swipe to see second photo.) Use the seam allowance guideline marked around the template to align the exact fussy cut you want, then trim around the template with your rotary cutter just as you would any other acrylic ruler. Simple as that! Makes fussy cutting those book covers a breeze!

One of my earliest memories is of my father hurrying my mother, brother and I into the family car and driving us to a large, secluded pond in the middle of nowhere at dusk one summer evening. I must have been three or four years old at most, but I remember it like it was yesterday. We arrived at the large pond just after dark, and I had no clue what we were doing there until my father had us roll all the windows down, then turned off the car and told us to listen. 

I’ve never heard such a chorus of frogs and crickets in my life. The lightning bugs were everywhere, their sweet, little glows filling the forest and field around us like golden twinkle lights. We sat together in the darkness for who knows how long, and it was nothing short of magical. ✨

I’ve gotten lots of messages on IG and Etsy from folks wondering where they can purchase my gingerbread house pattern. The same happened when I made haunted houses this autumn. So let’s clear up any confusion, shall we?

I have two “house patterns” in my Etsy shop. My “Home for the Holidays” pattern features FPP templates that allow you to design and “construct” your own house quilt block. It comes with various window and door options, an optional chimney, different rooflines, etc. it also includes three tree patterns with optional tree stand bases. My “Snow Place Like Home” pattern features an A-Frame house and optional snow globe surround. If you own both patterns, you can swap out any of the houses into the snow globe design. Swipe to see examples of projects I’ve made using these two patterns. 

Think of my patterns as “legos for quilters.” I design my patterns with the hopes of encouraging the maker to get creative. Make haunted houses, gingerbread houses, Valentine’s houses, summer houses, or even a house that looks like your own! The sky’s the limit when it comes to your creativity with these patterns.
